There are several stages where the kerning data is accessed. For me the more important part is during editing the font data in the UI, not the generating of the feature code. 
I think the confusion comes form the fact that the classes are defined on a single glyph. The classes (left/right/top/bottom) collects all glyphs that are similar on that side. The kerning is defined on pairs, so here the left/right mean the glyph on that side of the pair. The right side of the left glyph is kerned to the left side of the right glyph. I know that this can be confusing but this is how I managed to get it together.

Just for reference a comparison between LTR and RTL:
```
kerningLTR = {
	m01 = {
		"@MMK_L_A_R" = {
			"@MMK_R_B_L" = -20;
		};
	};
};
kerningRTL = {
	m01 = {
		"@MMK_R_alef_L" = {
			"@MMK_L_beh_R" = -50;
		};
	};
};
```

